<exercises xml:id="exercises-">
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain, in your own words, why <xref ref="thm-SlightlyDifferentFunctions"/> is true.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Consider the following limit:
                <me>
                    \lim_{x\to 3} \left(\frac{2x^2-5x-3}{x^2+5x-24}\right)
                </me>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Confirm that this limit has an indeterminate form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate the limit.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    When you were evaluating the limit, you likely <q>cancelled</q> a factor of <m>(x-3)</m> from the numerator and denominator. Why might you have known, before factoring anything, that <m>(x-3)</m> would be a factor shared in the numerator and denominator?
                </p>
                <p>
                    For instance, how did you know it wasn't going to be <m>(x-4)</m> or <m>(x+1)</m> or something else?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Consider the following limit:
                <me>
                    \lim_{x\to}
                </me>
                
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the algebra tricks from <xref ref="strat-AlgebraicManipulationsLimits"/> to evaluate each limit.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} \left(\frac{x^2-4}{x^2+3x-10}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to-1} \left(\frac{2x^2+x-1}{x+1}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to4} \left(\frac{4-x}{x-4}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to1} \left(\frac{\sqrt{x+3}-2}{x-1}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to2} \left(\frac{\sqrt{x^2-1} - \sqrt{x+1}}{x-2}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h\to0} \left(\frac{\sqrt{a+h}-\sqrt{a}}{h}\right)</m> where <m>a</m> is some non-negative real number
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to3} \left(\frac{\frac{1}{t}- \frac{1}{3}}{t-3}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to6} \left(\frac{\frac{t+1}{t-1} - \frac{7}{11-t}}{t-6}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h\to0} \left(\frac{\frac{1}{a+h}-\frac{1}{a}}{h}\right)</m> where <m>a</m> is some real number
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    
</exercises>